The paper deals with a combinatorial optimization problem related to graph coloring, which suggests that it could belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) category. The use of polyhedral methods to study the problem and derive valid inequalities suggests that it could also belong to the Computational Geometry (cs.CG) category. The focus on connected subgraphs and the use of graph-theoretic concepts suggest that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. The study of inequalities and facets suggests that it could belong to the Game Theory and Economics (cs.GT) category. Finally, the application of the problem to mobile networks suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category.
